## 3. Executive Summary

This project delivers a web-based AI application that detects and classifies steel surface defects using a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), specifically EfficientNet-B0, trained on the NEU Steel Surface Defect Database. The platform allows Quality Inspectors and Factory Operators to upload images or use a live webcam feed to detect six defect types in real time, view confidence scores and Grad-CAM explainability heatmaps, and track inspection history through a dashboard.

The system is scoped as a **single-student, 45-day MVP build**. It is deliberately kept to a monolithic, modular architecture (React + FastAPI + PostgreSQL) — no microservices, no Kubernetes, no distributed inference. The realistic goal is a working, demonstrable, defensible product, not a production-grade industrial system.

**Reality check:** the two highest-risk features are (1) achieving usable live-webcam inference speed in the browser/backend without GPU infrastructure, and (2) getting Grad-CAM to render correctly on a mobile-inverted-residual architecture like EfficientNet. Both are flagged as MVP-critical-but-fallback-ready in this document — if either slips, there are documented fallback plans rather than silent scope failure.

